# Memory Leaking in Rust with `Box::leak`

## What `Box::leak` Does

`Box::leak` converts a `Box<T>` into a `&'static mut T`, intentionally preventing the destructor from running and giving the value a `'static` lifetime.

```rust
use std::collections::HashMap;
use std::sync::OnceLock;

// ============================================================
// Example 1: Static configuration loaded at startup
// ============================================================

#[derive(Debug)]
struct AppConfig {
    database_url: String,
    max_connections: u32,
    feature_flags: HashMap<String, bool>,
}

impl AppConfig {
    fn new(database_url: &str, max_connections: u32) -> Self {
        let mut feature_flags = HashMap::new();
        feature_flags.insert("dark_mode".to_string(), true);
        feature_flags.insert("beta_features".to_string(), false);

        AppConfig {
            database_url: database_url.to_string(),
            max_connections,
            feature_flags,
        }
    }
}

impl Drop for AppConfig {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        // This will NEVER be called when we use Box::leak
        println!("AppConfig dropped (you won't see this with Box::leak)");
    }
}

/// Leaks config intentionally so it can be referenced with 'static lifetime
/// from anywhere in the program without synchronization overhead.
fn init_config(database_url: &str, max_connections: u32) -> &'static AppConfig {
    let config = Box::new(AppConfig::new(database_url, max_connections));
    Box::leak(config)
    // Memory is now "owned" by the program for its entire lifetime
}

